Stimulated by Bob's thread, &quot;A simple Question No Oxfordian will Answer&quot;,
I've been thinking about evidence in general and how we interpret it. Bob
seems to be asking Oxfordians to distinguish between different kinds of
evidence, and weigh up one kind against another. But that's a problem all by
itself. We'd have to agree on the categories. For example, Diana Price has
done a lot of work on a new kind of evidence involving something called
&quot;explicit terminology&quot;, which she introduces us to when dealing with
Jonson's De Shakespeare Nostrati. Just to remind you, the piece begins as
follows:-

I remember, the Players have often mentioned it as an
honour to Shakespeare that in his writing, (whatsoever
he penn'd), he never blotted out line.

Price cautions us, &quot;Nothing in De Shakespeare Nostrati describes a writer&quot;,
and then goes on to say: &quot;When Jonson referred to literary men, he used
explicit terminology&quot;, and quotes him on Beaumont, amongst others, as an
example of what she means by that: &quot;'For writing better I must envy thee'&quot;.
Unfortunately, she didn't give a definition of &quot;explicit terminology&quot; that
would enable us to judge the one quote against the other. I suppose that
must be our job. Now, if you eliminate what is common to both - namely, the
word &quot;writing&quot; (even though it might sound a bit terminologically explicit
to the layman) - it leaves you lining up &quot;better&quot; and &quot;envy&quot; as
terminologically explicit words against &quot;penn'd&quot; and &quot;blotted out&quot; to see
why Beaumont passes the test of terminological explicitness and Shakespeare
fails. And the answer is...well, I'm not sure what the answer is. I'm only
sure that she's sure that Beaumont wins it hands down. &quot;De Shakespeare
Nostrati is devoid of any such *literary* terminology&quot;, she says (her
emphasis). Obviously, though, if &quot;writing&quot; doesn't refer to writing (except
with Beaumont, where it does), it must refer to something else. It leaves us
pondering the knotty question of what kind of activity that opening
paragraph of De Shakespeare Nostrati is describing. &quot;Writing&quot;, &quot;penn'd&quot; and
&quot;blotted out&quot; constitute *some* kind of terminology, we think - but in what
area of human endeavour? And is it explicit?

Maybe we could do a little collective work on this, similar to what we're
doing on the sonnets - a group effort. Why doesn't some Oxfordian kick off
the match by clarifying this complicated &quot;explicit terminology&quot; thing? But I
doubt Malcrowleyo would want to do it, since there's no bawdy involved, and
Mary Queen of Scots doesn't come into it anywhere. So I think that just
leaves Lynne.

Lynne - over to you. What is it that Shakespeare is doing when he's writing,
penning or blotting out?

Buffalo

