No it isn't. We should start by correctly identifying the question. (Have
you been taking Thornton's Thicko Tablets?)
To make it easier I shall erase the name from Jonson's piece. It's now
called De Mr.X Nostrati.

I remember, the Players have often mentioned it as an
honour to Mr X that in his writing, (whatsoever
he penn'd), he never blotted out line.

Diana Priceless has told us that &quot;There is nothing in De Mr X Nostrati that
identifies a writer&quot;, and your mission, should you choose to accept it, is
to tell us what Mr X is being described as doing in that paragraph instead
of writing. Something that seems to involve a quill, ink and perhaps paper.
Is it solving crossword puzzles? Or doing the family accounts? Or some other
thing that I haven't thought of? Whatever it is, it makes Mr X worth an
article in Jonson's notebook.

