Like Lynne, I have no wish to get into a discussion about
what Diana Price may or may not have meant by some phrase
she used, partly because I haven't read her book, but
mainly because I am far more interested in what *Jonson*
may have meant. There is little doubt that this particular
passage is a hurdle which anyone of an anti-Stratfordian
turn of mind needs to clear if they are not to leave them-
selves open to the criticism of ignoring any evidence
which runs counter to their views.

As always with this sort of thing, of course, one's idea
of what such an extract might mean will be very influenced
by what one believes the background situation to be. Strat-
fordians will therefore read it assuming that Jonson is
referring to Shakespeare as the sole writer of the plays
attributed to him, and interpret it accordingly. This then
becomes in their minds the &quot;right&quot; answer, and any other
interpretation wrong. My view is that another meaning can
be taken from his words which better fits what *I* think
is the probable background situation, and that *if* my
scenario is correct, then my interpretation is more likely
to be the right one. In neither case, however, can Jonson's
words be taken as evidence on behalf of one story to the
*exclusion* of the other.

The background situation, as I see it, is (to quote my
essay on the monument) &quot;that Marlowe and Shakespeare
probably worked as a team, using the name of the latter
as a sort of 'trading name' for the partnership. Marlowe
was responsible for by far the greater part of any writing
that was done, but Shakespeare was the public face, the
provider (and polisher up) of the scripts, the interface
with the players, provider of the 'sides' they worked from,
and the apparent authority on what the plays were all about,
how they should be presented, etc.&quot;

So, with that in mind, let's look at Jonson's words,

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I remember, the Players have often mentioned it as an
&gt; honour to Shakespeare, that in his writing (whatsoever
&gt; he penn'd) hee never blotted out line.

"/>

If we ignore for a moment the bit in parentheses, It seems
fairly obvious that the Players are talking about writings
which are in Shakespeare's own hand and which he has given
to them.

Acknowledging the immense help that Clark Holloway's
page is in doing such a thing, let us look at the ways in
which Jonson tends to use the verb 'to write', or forms
of it, in his plays. They seem to fall into roughly three
groups, not unlike how we would use the word today:

1) The physical activity of setting down words etc on
paper or the like. I found about 3 examples of this.

2) Reporting or assembling information and setting it down,
such as the writing of annals or day-to-day letters.
This is the most common use, my having found 14 in all.

3) An activity requiring imagination and intended to affect
the emotions, such as the creation of verse, plays,
speeches, songs, love-letters. I found 7 of these.

We must of course assume that the Players are referring to
plays they have been given, but the reference to what is
'blotted out' tends to give the physical activity more
emphasis. It is also worth noting that the word is
'writing' rather than 'writings', which has a similar
tendency to push it in that direction.

It needn't be, but I take the parentheses to indicate that
this is an aside by Jonson, and not what the Players have
said. If it were from their words, then they would be
probably saying that no matter what type of thing he wrote
- whether comedy, history or tragedy, for example - it was
always like this. One might wonder why it was necessary to
amplify it in this way of course, but it is possible.

If it is his additional comment, however, we perhaps need
to look a little more closely at those words 'whatsoever'
and 'penned'.

He tended to use 'whatsoever' to mean either 'anything
which' or 'no matter what'.

Examples (both from *Every Man out of His Humour*) are:

and hence we do conclude,
That whatsoe'er hath Fluxure and Humidity,
As wanting power to contain it self,
Is Humour.
('anything which')

Nay, look you Carlo: this is my humour now! I
have Land and Mony, my Friends left me well,
and I will be a Gentleman whatsoever it cost me.
('no matter what')

It is when we come to the verb 'pen' and its variants
(and excluding any 'shut in' meaning) that it gets
interesting, and surprising as far as I was concerned.
Without exception, every one of the 17 examples I found
in Jonson was of the third type I mentioned above, the
one requiring imagination. He does therefore clearly
distinguish the two words as to his usage of them.

If, then, we assume that a similar distinction is being
made in *Timber*, and if the word 'penned' is emphasized,
he could be saying that in the plays they have received
in Shakespeare's handwriting (no matter what he composed
himself) he had never blotted out a line.

And is Jonson perhaps objecting to 'a thousand' lines
among those which he knows full well that Shakespeare,
&quot;You know what he's like&quot;, must have added to the ones
he received from you-know-who?

Now I would like to move on to that bit at the end of the
extract:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Many times hee fell into those things, could not escape
&gt; laughter: As when hee said in the person of Cæsar, one
&gt; speaking to him; Cæsar thou dost me wrong. Hee replyed:
&gt; Cæsar did never wrong, but with just cause: and such like;
&gt; which were ridiculous.

"/>

I want to suggest something which I don't think has been
suggested before (at least not here), which is that
Jonson is referring to a speech he half-remembers in his
own *Sejanus*, in which we know Shakespeare acted.
Sejanus (Burbage?) addresses Tiberius (Shakespeare?):

Sej. Cæsar doth wrong
His Dignity and Safety, thus to mourn
The deserv'd End of so profest a Traitor,
And doth, by this his Lenity, instruct
Others as factious, to the like Offence.
Tib. The Confiscation meerly of his State
Had been enough.

I think it quite likely that, before carrying on with his
'correct' words, Shakespeare ad-libbed the line that
Jonson - typical playwright - remembers much better!

And if I am right in this, then we may safely assume that
virtually everything he says about Shakespeare from around
where he claims to have &quot;loved the man&quot; is about Shake-
speare as a witty and imaginative, if over-enthusiastic,
person, rather than Shakespeare (necessarily) as a writer.

One final thought about that part of the extract:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; ... (for I lov'd the man, and doe
&gt; honour his memory (on this side Idolatry) as much as
&gt; any.)

"/>

He loved the *man* and honoured his memory as much as
any, but did *not* idolize him as others apparently did.
Why not, I wonder?

Peter F.
