Not if the First Folio means anything, since Jonson is only repeating an
implicit criticism he made in his encomium - namely, his belief that
Shakespeare should have cut and revised his texts more than he did. The
criticism is only implicit, since it would not be appropriate in a
celebratory document like the First Folio to voice such reservations
outright. The extended passage that deals with Shakespeare's &quot;Art&quot; (meaning
his learned technique rather than his native talent) describes the process
by which first thoughts are cut and shaped, a process in which &quot;blotting out
line&quot; would play a big part. Here in his private notebook, that criticism
can be more explicit. If you are determined to construct a two-author
theory, you would have to show how this criticism is a reference to the
inferiority of Shakespeare's additions to Marlowe's original - and show it
in the First Folio, not just by some ingenious re-interpretation of words
like &quot;writing&quot; and &quot;penn'd&quot; in Jonson's private notebook.

