Well, still leaving aside the difference between &quot;writing&quot; and &quot;writings&quot;,
and focussing on the distinction between &quot;pen&quot; and &quot;write&quot;, it looks like
the meaning of &quot;write&quot; is more important. I won't dispute that &quot;pen&quot; is
always associated with &quot;compose&quot; in Jonson's usage. But then neither of us
is disputing that that is the meaning of &quot;penn'd&quot; in De Shakespeare
Nostrati. So it comes down to whether or not Jonson would use &quot;write&quot; to
mean the same thing.

I've only looked at Timber, but there is enough in there to throw doubt on
your claim.

&quot;For a man that doth me an injury after a courtesie, takes
not away the courtesie, but defaces it: As he that writes other verses
upon my verses, takes not away the first Letters, but hides them.&quot;

I'll grant you that one. Even though &quot;verses&quot; suggests he should use
&quot;penning&quot;, the metaphor is to do with the smothering of another's physical
writing with your own.

But I wouldn't concede this one:-

&quot;Nothing is fashionable, till it bee deform'd; and this is to write like a
Gentleman&quot;

Surely he isn't referring to calligraphy or anything like that. It's a
reference to style.

&quot;There are never wanting, that dare preferre the worst Preachers, the worst
Pleaders, the worst Poets: not that the better have left to write, or speake
better, but that they that heare them judge worse;

Ditto, I think. The reference is to the quality of the content - more a
&quot;penning&quot; type of writing.

&quot;Others there are, that have no composition at all; but a kind of tuneing,
and riming fall, in {w}hat they write.&quot;

Ditto again. The reference is to the content.

&quot;They write a verse, as smooth, as soft, as creame; In which there is no
torrent, nor scarce streame.&quot;

That one speaks for itself. Definitely a &quot;penning&quot; type of writing.

And I think all the following fall into the &quot;penning&quot; category:-

&quot;Some, that turne over all bookes, and are equally searching in all papers,
that write out of what they presently find or meet, without choice;&quot;

&quot;These in all they write, confesse still what bookes they have read last; &quot;

&quot;How he doth raigne in mens affections; how invade, and breake in upon them;
and makes their minds like the thing he writes.&quot;

&quot;I confesse, my Lord, they will seeme but petty, and minute things I shall
offer to you, being writ for children, and of them.

&quot;Which was, as to tell him, he could not write a verse.&quot;

So I can't see it. Suggesting different meanings for &quot;write&quot; and &quot;pen&quot; in De
Shakespeare Nostrati depends on showing that Jonson made the distinction
consistently in his work, and it looks to me that he didn't. Although I
agree that &quot;pen&quot; is exclusively used for literary composition, he has used
&quot;write&quot; often enough in the same context that any subtle distinction he
might have been making in De Shakespeare Nostrati would have been lost on
his readers.

Such a case as you might have rests on any difference between the meaning of
&quot;writing&quot; and &quot;writings&quot;. I'll concede that the sentence in question is the
only place in Timber where he used &quot;writing&quot;, having used &quot;writings&quot;
everywhere else to refer to a body of literary work. But I have to express
the same doubt about whether any of his contempories would pick it up. After
all, the &quot;s&quot; isn't the only letter he dropped from that sentence. &quot;Never
blotted out line&quot; has a missing &quot;a&quot;. Why wouldn't they think (as I think)
that it's just a calligraphic error?

It's a good try, Peter. But really, it's tenuous.

