In 1982, William Honey published his theory that it was
*Shakespeare* who was in fact killed in 1593, with the
object of allowing Marlowe from then on to take over his
identity as William Shakespeare. In other words, that
Marlowe *was* Shakespeare, to use Jim's phrase (and
vice versa). It is, as I said, not an idea to which I have
ever subscribed.

As far as what I do think most probably happened, this
is what I posted here (to Richard Nathan) *five and a
half years ago*, on 22 Jan 1999:

If you go to the website shown below and click on
'A Deception in Deptford' you will see the follow-
ing words, which state fairly clearly where I stand
on this.

Christopher Marlowe's alleged death
is investigated by Peter Farey
And new evidence is presented, which shows:
. that Marlowe was, beyond reasonable doubt, still
alive two years after his supposed death in May
1593,
. that his survival would have made possible a
collaboration explaining the exceptional influence
Marlowe is said to have had upon the works of
Shakespeare,
. that Marlowe probably played a major part in such
a collaboration.

When I say 'beyond reasonable doubt', I am thinking
of a high probability (p &gt;.99) and when I say 'probably'
I am merely saying that it is more likely than not
(p &gt;.5).

The essay itself had been uploaded and I had pointed it
out to HLAS a couple of months *before* the ancient post
which Jim has managed to find, and (beyond some changes
in the stated confidence levels), my views are in no way
different now from what I said then.

